1: A new disk is attached â€” You must partition, format, and mount it
Commands:
lsblk
fdisk /dev/sdc   # create /dev/sdc1
mkfs.xfs /dev/sdc1
mkdir /appdata
mount /dev/sdc1 /appdata
echo "/dev/sdc1 /appdata xfs defaults 0 0" >> /etc/fstab

Why this is real?

This happens during adding storage for applications, logs, backup, database, or Docker/OCP storage.

ðŸŸ¦ SCENARIO 2: Developer complains â€œdisk is fullâ€
Check disks:
df -h
du -sh /var/log/*

Found /data disk is not mounted (mount failed after reboot)
Fix:
mount -a


If error â†’ check fstab syntax.

ðŸŸ¨ SCENARIO 3: NFS Share needs to be mounted for application
Test NFS:
showmount -e 10.0.0.20

Mount:
mount -t nfs 10.0.0.20:/sapdata /mnt/sap

Permanent:
10.0.0.20:/sapdata  /mnt/sap  nfs  defaults  0 0

ðŸŸ¥ SCENARIO 4: "device is busy" when trying to unmount
Issue:
umount /data
umount: /data: target is busy.

Solution: find who is using it
lsof | grep /data
fuser -m /data


Kill processes:

fuser -km /data
umount /data

ðŸŸ§ SCENARIO 5: ISO file needs to be mounted
mount -o loop RHEL9.iso /mnt/iso


Unmount:

umount /mnt/iso

