ðŸ¢ 6. REAL COMPANY SCENARIOS (Very Common)
----------------------------
â­ Scenario A â€” Application server needs a separate /app mount

Company wants separate storage for application logs.

Solution:
fdisk /dev/sdb
mkfs.xfs /dev/sdb1
mkdir /app
mount /dev/sdb1 /app
echo "/dev/sdb1 /app xfs defaults 0 0" >> /etc/fstab

â­ Scenario B â€” Database (MySQL/PostgreSQL) needs separate storage

DB team asks for separate mount for /var/lib/mysql.

Steps:

Stop DB

Mount new disk

Copy old data

Update fstab

â­ Scenario C â€” Kubernetes/OpenShift storage

Storage team provides new disk for container logs.

Mount under:

/var/lib/containers
/var/lib/kubelet


Requires:

mount /dev/sdc1 /var/lib/containers

â­ Scenario D â€” Programmer accidentally deleted fstab entry

System fails to mount important disk â†’ website down.

Fix:

mount -a
vim /etc/fstab

â­ Scenario E â€” Backup team wants NFS mount

Mount backup storage:

mount -t nfs backupserver:/archive /mnt/backup


Add in fstab:

backupserver:/archive /mnt/backup  nfs  defaults 0 0



##########################################---------------------------------------------------############################################

Real-Time Enterprise Scenarios (VERY IMPORTANT)
Scenario 1: Application not starting because config file is missing

Developer says:

â€œMy app cannot find config.ymlâ€

You run:

find / -name config.yml 2>/dev/null


You discover it is under /opt/app/conf/config.yml.
You update the service file:

Environment="CONFIG_PATH=/opt/app/conf/config.yml"
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl restart myapp

Scenario 2: Server disk full; find largest files
find / -type f -size +500M -exec ls -lh {} \; 2>/dev/null


or easier:

du -sh /* | sort -h


You find /var/log/messages is 8GB â†’ rotate logs:

logrotate -f /etc/logrotate.conf

Scenario 3: Find world-writable files (Security Audit)

Security team asks:

find / -perm -002 -type f 2>/dev/null


Fix:

chmod o-w <file>

Scenario 4: Identify files changed in the last 10 minutes

Useful for debugging unauthorized change.

find / -mmin -10 2>/dev/null

Scenario 5: Find all files created by a terminated employee
find /home -user john


Then archive or transfer:

tar -czf john_backup.tar.gz /home/john

ðŸ”´ 3. Common Issues + Solutions
âŒ Issue 1: locate gives no result
locate nginx.conf


No output.

âœ” Fix: update the database

sudo updatedb

âŒ Issue 2: find shows many permission denied errors
find / -name test


âœ” Fix:

find / -name test 2>/dev/null


or run as root.

âŒ Issue 3: find command is slow

âœ” Use specific paths:

âŒ BAD:

find / -name server.crt


âœ” GOOD:

find /etc -name server.crt

âŒ Issue 4: Find symbolic link target
readlink -f /usr/bin/python

âŒ Issue 5: Cannot find where a package installed files**

Example:

rpm -ql httpd

ðŸ”´ 4. Interview Questions & Answers (Very Common)
Q1: Difference between find and locate?

Answer:

find searches the filesystem in real time â†’ slower, always accurate

locate uses a prebuilt database â†’ very fast but may be outdated

Q2: How to find files modified in last 24 hours?
find / -mtime -1

Q3: How to find & delete .log files bigger than 100MB?
find /var/log -name "*.log" -size +100M -delete

Q4: How to find all files owned by a specific user?
find / -user username

Q5: What is the difference between whereis and which?

which â†’ executable path in $PATH

whereis â†’ binary + source + man-page locations

Q6: A developer says â€œmy script is using wrong python version.â€ What do you check?
which python
type python

ðŸ”´ 5. Real Company Use Cases (asked in RHCSA job roles)
Use Case 1: Security Audit

Security team asks:

â€œFind all SUID and SGID files.â€

Command:

